column2: The Trustee For The Harold Mitchell Foundation Fund
column49: The Harold Mitchell Foundation Fund works with organisations that want to make a difference in Australia and the region. The Fund is increasingly focused on four key areas: health, with a focus on mental health and disadvantage, as well as medical research; education, with a focus on building the next generation of Australian leaders; arts, with a focus on big ideas that place Australia on the world map; and our region, with a focus on Australia_Ü_s leadership role. The Mitchell Institute is one of the Fund_Ü_s ongoing projects, a venture in partnership with Victoria University, dedicated to tackling health and education policy issues affecting Australia. The Mitchell Institute aims to transform educational and health outcomes for people in our community by identifying the critical health and education issues in Australia that would benefit from deep enquiry, robust research, and vigorous debate to positively influence public policy and ultimately, the lives of people in our community. The Institute's focus is on socially and economically disadvantaged communities and the transformational change effective education and good health can deliver. Another of the Fund_Ü_s key ongoing projects include the health travel fellowships, which enable promising young medical scientists to travel overseas to participate in seminal conferences, and receive mentoring and support from leading medical specialists. They will bring this experience back to Australia to begin a lifetime of collaboration.

column2: Alertness Crc Ltd
column49: The Alertness CRC is making significant progress towards the prevention and control of sleep loss and sleep disorders in human beings and improvements in alertness, safety, productivity and health. The sophisticated research program is designed to provide genuine innovation in sleep health and alertness management and is generating a unique combination of data that flows across projects to service multiple research strategies. The four platform projects continue to generate large data collection _ÜÛengines_Ü_ for the consortium in the laboratory; the clinic; and in the field. These data feed a highly developed capability in biomathematical modelling and are managed via a comprehensive, scalable and searchable sleep alertness database allowing advanced data analysis and data mining. With strong engagement from many of the end user and academic participant organisations, the Alertness CRC has developed additional and more targeted project concepts that are taking advantage of the large datasets being generated and focused on key outputs. The overall structure of the Alertness CRC_Ü_s research comprise of three Program Leaders and six Theme Leaders facilitates high quality academic supervision of the research activities and has allowed the CRC to more closely monitor the ability of the project activities to generate high impact outputs in Sleep Health management. The Alertness CRC Education Committee continues to oversee comprehensive and diverse education and training component. With a total of 24 post doctoral fellows active in the research program at of 30 June 2016, these early career researchers have been given prominent roles in project teams with some taking on Project Leader positions. This responsibility and the ability to interact with senior end user representatives is a key factor in building capacity, aligning their skills and expertise to output driven research and exposing them to industry practices and pressures.The PhD program includes 18 students currently enrolled and integrated into the platform projects and core activities of the CRC. The Master program currently includes two students and is particularly vital to the creation of a _ÜÛpipeline_Ü_ of PhD candidates. The CRC has also supported a number of shorter term vacation scholarships.The CRC has worked closely with the Sleep Health Foundation (SHF) and through the SHF, the Alertness CRC has access to an expanded network of industry stakeholders and consumer groups particularly in the area of sleep health service delivery. Working with the SHF, the CRC is seeking to further influence the national health agenda in recognition of the importance of sleep health by reporting data on economic impact of sleep disruption and sleep disorders.

column49: Board of Management Report for the year ending August 31st 2016Board members all act in an honorary capacityGovernance statement: Heartbeat Victoria is a Victorian state association founded in 1984 and incorporated under the Association Incorporation Act 1981(Vic). It is a not for profit charitable organisation, registered under the Australian Charities and Not-For-Profit Commission (ACNC). Heartbeat Victoria Council Inc. is the umbrella organisation for Heartbeat affiliates and branches. (Currently 9) Heartbeat Victoria has three Affiliates they are independently incorporated. The Rules are available on the Consumer Affairs Victoria website. Strategic Plan; The Board of Management are currently guided by Heartbeat Victoria Inc. Strategic Plan 2015-17. We are focused on building and maintaining a sustainable organisation which values its entire membership.  Our vision to be an excellent well recognised support organisation which assists in improving the emotional, social, and physical wellbeing of people living with heart disease or heart condition is the main focus of our objectives. The contracting of a consultant to assist the Board has enabled the professional development of the organisation to provide the best strategies to support our members and plan to further enhance and spread of the benefits of heart peer support groups across the state. The Board is currently working on improving communication and promotion of Heartbeats_Ü_ vision, mission and values to appropriate stake holders with improved promotional material, use of Facebook and currently developing  a contemporary website. Through the support of our consultant we now have a draft copy of Heartbeat Victoria Policy and Procedure Manual. This will be a valuable tool for office bearers and committees in providing guidance in governance, administration and pre-formatted forms to them in their individual roles within the organisation. Financial Sustainability: The Board of Management now has a board member who is a Charted Accountant to guide the development of a financial plan that ensures the financial sustainability of Heartbeat Victoria Council Inc. and its affiliates and branches. column49: Variety empowers Australian children who are sick, disadvantaged or have special needs to live laugh and learn.  Our vision is for all Australian children to reach their full potential regardless of ability or background.  In 2016 Variety Victoria directly impacted 2155 children across Victoria by providing grants through our three key programs - Freedom, Future and Caring for Kids.  We provided 67 grants through our Freedom program, helping 1851 children gain independence by providing financial support for mobility equipment, positioning and in-home care needs.  This includes the provision of custom modified tricycle and bikes, wheelchairs, specialist car seats and more.  We provided 43 grants through our Future Kids program helping 7117 children realize their potential by providing financial support for education and communication equipment. This includes the provision of specialist computer packages, communication devices, scholarships, camps, regional and special education school support, sensory playgrounds,   and more. We provided 8 grants through our Caring for Kids program, by providing 187 children with medical items and care equipment so that sick children can live happy, healthy lives. This includes nebulisers, electric beds for families at home, supporting paediatric hospital wards, children's respite and rehabilitation centres and more.

column2: The Trustee For Pet Medical Crisis Fund
column49: The Pet Medical Crisis Fund (PMCF) is a unique Australian charity which raises funds to be used for Victorian residents in necessitous circumstances whose pets are in danger of being unnecessarily euthanized due to financial difficulties.    We are a registered, tax deductible, GST exempt, not for profit charity and relies on public donations and unpaid volunteers to operate a charitable service available to all veterinary clinic clients in Victoria.    The PMCF relies on unpaid volunteers and is run by the founder, Jennifer Hunt, who aims to get 100% of donations to assist pensioners and disadvantaged pet owners to save their pet's lives.  The charity relies on public donations, is run by unpaid volunteers and expects veterinary care to be not for profit in keeping with our charitable status so as to optimise effectiveness of donations.    When a pet becomes unwell and is in danger of being unnecessarily euthanized the PMCF uses a case-by-case process to determine suitability for assistance:    PMCF asks the vet to explain the pet and owner's circumstances and to outline the plan of care.  We ask vets to discount their costs to being not for profit.  We then talk with the owner to determine their circumstances and whether they have exhausted all avenues of finding funds.  Once established as being in necessitous circumstances, we ask the owner how much they can put towards the cost of veterinary care and aim to bridge the gap up to a maximum of $1,000.  If meeting our criteria (ie. the owner has explained their circumstances that leave them in necessitous circumstances, they have exhausted all sources of finding funds to provide veterinary care and the pet is in danger of being unnecessarily euthanized as explained by a registered veterinarian) the charity determines eligibility and amount to be donated to save the pet's life.  We ask for a social story - where the pet came from, why they are important to their owner, social / financial circumstances, what illness / injury the pet has sustained and what is needed to be done to save their lives.    We ask for clear photos to be sent electronically and to be used on our Facebook page to show the charity's activities and create transparency.  Owners are asked to participate by allowing the local (or larger) media to run the story, to thank the PMCF and to allow our website to be published for donations to be made to assist the next case.  The charity commenced in 2010 and since 'getting our stride' in 2012 we have assisted over 350 pensioner's to prevent their pets from being unnecessarily euthanized.

column2: Bridgingworx Limited
column49: Bridging Worx has moved ahead with lightning speed _Ü_ learning and growing all the way, but coming out stronger on the other side. It is with awe and pride that I share with you the 2015/2016 financial year.  Bridging Worx was on the move once again, settling in to our new office in Gladstone Park. We are now settled in and confident that this will be our base for quite some time to come. We also made thedecision to expand to where our services are located, setting up an office in Armstrong Street, Ballarat.This year saw the departure if our General Manager as well as our Financial Controller as we aimed toreduce overheads and streamline processes/services to be able to focus our much needed resources onproviding outcomes for the people we support. We also saw the departure of our Disability ServicesManager, Melissa Pool. This was not a goodbye, with her taking up a position on our Board, enablingher to remain actively involved in the strategic direction and growth of the organisation. This lead to anopportunity for promotion for our Disability Services Co-ordinator Andre Cofre, seeing him take on therole of Disability Services Manager in October of 2016. Andre has proven to be a huge asset to theorganisation and has been instrumental in assisting me with the growth and future direction of BridgingWorx to ensure it becomes a disability service provider of choice. The rollout of the National Disability Insurance Scheme (NDIS) within the North East MetropolitanArea (NEMA) has seen us working diligently to ensure that we are well prepared and well placed for the roll out for our clients within the Central Highlands region in January 2017. I'm also extremely proud of the funding extension in our Justice Program Genesis working with Pacific & Maori (CALD) background inmates in their pre and post release from Prison.  Our Emerge Program (Youth Diversionary for Pacific & Maori) has grown in strengths with a strategic view to expand the program into mainstream.  This is an ever changing landscape, but we are excited about the benefits the NDIS will provide for people with disability and we are confident that the work we have been doing, and we will continue to do will prove fruitful in the long term not only for the organisation, but for the people we continue to support. I am extremely proud of the team I have both working both for me and with me and I look forward to another year of challenges, growth and positive outcomes ahead for all.

VALID engages at both the individual and systemic levels to serve as an effective conduit for the lived experience of people with intellectual disability and their families, and an effective contributor to policy development. VALID's Community Development brings together citizens with disabilities, and their supporters, to engage with individual advocacy concerns and to connect them with systemic advocacy strategies to make positive change. column2: Children's Cancer Foundation
column49: The Children's Cancer Foundation's mission is to enable children with cancer to access the world_Ü_s best treatment and support and to build awareness of childhood cancer in the community and within governments.  Through an extensive grant making program, the Foundation supports families undergoing treatment, partners with hospitals to deliver clinical excellence and funds clinical research and clinical trials with the aim to develop new and kinder treatments for children with cancer. In 2015/16 the Foundation supported families through the stress of cancer treatment by funding the salaries of Family Resource Coordinators, and by providing therapeutic storybooks and Music and Art Therapy to assist children with adapting to treatment. The Foundation also funded The Beaded Journey, a therapeutic program which helps each patient mark every treatment milestone with a special bead; this program assists children and their families to cope with their cancer experience and relate their experience visually. In 2017 the Foundation will announce major new grants for projects that span the cancer treatment journey, from family support and clinical care to ground breaking clinical research and clinical trials, including one national project.At all times, the Foundation endeavours to raise funds in a way which is both efficient and ethical. The Foundation does not conduct public raffles or telemarketing. Nor do we receive government funding. Funds are raised through The Million Dollar Lunch, community fundraising, corporate sponsorship and donations. A volunteer board of directors and a large team of dedicated volunteers help us maximise our fundraising income, while the generosity of many pro bono supporters _Ü_ office space, marketing, design, legal and insurance _Ü_ ensure that our administration overheads over the past 5 years have averaged just 9%. For the latest news from the Foundation, visit: http://childrenscancerfoundation.com.au/news

column2: The Trustee For Echo-elderly Citizens Help Organisation Inc.
column49: The focus of ECHO Inc is essentially to assist persons in Victoria who through misfortune cannot help themselves and have missed out from the welfare system. To undertake such a task in a small way requires funds. ECHO has assisted other charities in intersection tin shake collections building up expertise and knowledge in the field. The outcome of this program is that scarce funds are collected and distributed to much needed causes; the collectors themselves feel a net worth and self esteem in not only raising funds but also earning income rather than being on welfare.During the past year the money raised by ECHO which was not forwarded to partner charity organisations was used to purchase or trade in medical aids such as electric wheelchairs, walkers and shower aids. These are products for which there are extended waiting lists from different levels of Government. We were able to source and place two electric wheel chairs which were provided to housebound clients.Another activity we have has been the receipt of donated goods for distribution to those less fortunate. We have an active blanket program in the Winter and we provide some food relief to those in need who are drawn to our attention. A number of our collectors have not had the benefit of education and in this fast tech world are left behind. We are assisting some of these people to access programs which they are entitled to through local Library computers .There is much more to be done and if we can expand our fundraising then we shall be able to do more in the future

Not being sick does not mean we are well! A balanced lifestyle includes good nutrition, regular physical activity, social contact with family and friends and making choices that allow these priorities to find balance in our busy, modern lifestyle. column49: The principal purpose of the Association is to Educate, Engage and Empower people to sharetheir time and resources to assist benevolent causes and promote greater equality and harmonyin society.The activities in the 2016 financial year was predominantly focused on the development of the ShareTree mobile application and the Character and Culture Development Program. The activities pertaining to the three pillars of ShareTree namely Educate, Engage and Empower consisted of:Educate:- Working with the software developer to develop the Educate pillar of the ShareTree mobile application. The Educate pillar is based on cultivating character through language and behaviour.- Working with The Virtues Project Facilitators to develop the Character and Culture Development Program. - Delivering of the Character and Culture Development Program to organisations- Working with schools to scope the Character and Culture Development Program.- Maintained the ShareTree Facebook page.Engage:- Working with the software developer to develop the Engage pillar of the ShareTree mobile application. The Engage pillar is based on cultivating community by encouraging people and organisations to share time and resources with community organisations. Community organisations includes charities, not for profit organisations and schools.Empower:- Working with the software developer to develop the Empower pillar of the ShareTree mobile application. The Empower pillar is based on cultivating change through conscientious consumer choices.- Working with ShareTree seed funded businesses, where ShareTree is a 50% investor. These investments and subsequent returns ensure ShareTree maintains its operations.

column2: The Trustee For The Pierce Armstrong Foundation
column49: The charity's investment activities generated returns to fund the donations granted to various beneficiaries who applied to the charity.
